se":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63127"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA particular gram-negative rod is a common cause of diarrhoeal outbreaks in Australia. The organism is typically acquired through contaminated poultry, milk or water. Infection results in watery diarrhoea that may progress to invasive, haemorrhagic colitis. The pathogen multiplies in the gut and produces locally-acting cytotoxins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for this clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shigella species","Bacillus cereus","Campylobacter jejuni","Salmonella species","Yersinia enterocolitica"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter jejuni\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E infection. The organism is a curved gram-negative rod that is one of the most common causes of bacterial gastroenteritis worldwide. Contaminated poultry is the primary source of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can cause bloody diarrhoea, it is typically associated with person-to-person transmission rather than food contamination. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBacillus cereus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-positive organism that causes a toxin-mediated food poisoning with rapid onset. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESalmonella\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes more systemic symptoms including fever. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYersinia enterocolitica\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E infection is less common and often associated with consumption of contaminated pork.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Campylobacter is a gram-negative rod that commonly causes food-borne gastroenteritis through contaminated poultry, milk, or water.","Campylobacter infection typically presents with watery diarrhoea and can progress to invasive, haemorrhagic colitis.","The pathogen multiplies in the gut and produces local cytotoxins that contribute to disease."],"references":["Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802.","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338","Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal Infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. 2015 May 19:707\u201334. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-19674-9_50. PMCID: PMC7123654","Kotloff KL. Bacterial diarrhoea. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2022 Apr 1;34(2):147-155. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000001107. PMID: 35165210","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T09:02:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T09:03:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8128"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63127"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https